               <msContents>
                  <summary>The <title>Tajzīyat al-Amṣār va Tazjīyat al-Aʻṣār</title> (The
                     Progression of Cities and Procession of Ages) by <persName>ʻAbd Allāh ibn Faz̤l
                        Allāh (ca. 1264–1329), known as <addName>Vaṣṣāf</addName>
                        (Panegyrist)</persName>, hence often called <title>Tārīkh-i Vaṣṣāf</title>
                     (History of Vaṣṣāf). The author commenced the work in 699 AH (1299–1300 CE) and
                     dedicated it to his patron, the Mongol ruler <persName>Ghāzān Khān</persName>.
                     He intended it to continue earlier histories of the Mongols chronicling the
                     reigns of <persName role="subject" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/100172770/"
                        key="person_100172770">Changiz (Genghis) Khān (b. 1162, r.
                        1206–1227)</persName> and his descendants. While a value source, the
                     author's artificial ornate prose style proves tedious to read, for in his
                     introduction, he only introduces himself on page 7, and reveals the title of
                     the work on page 16. This manuscript regrettably lacks a fifth and final volume
                     often found in the collection that continues to relate events of that dynasty
                     until 727 (1327 CE). While this manuscript lacks a colophon, the scribe who
                     copied it, possibly in the <placeName cert="medium" type="empire"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7024412" key="place_7024412">Ottoman
                        Empire</placeName> prepared and polished wove paper watermarked
                           <watermark><q xml:lang="en">Budgen and Willmott <date
                              calendar="#Gregorian" when="1808">1808</date></q></watermark> of
                        <settlement type="county" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/148861381"
                        >Kent</settlement> for the text and endpapers.</summary>
